@NODE GADGETS
@TITLE "15 The Gadget Summary"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                      @{B}The Gadget Summary@{UB}

  This is a brief summary of the configuration window gadgets and
  their purpose. It is meant as a gadget function overview.

  The DRAWER gadget defines a drawer button.

  The EXECUTABLE gadget defines an executable button.

  The SCRIPT gadget defines a script button.

  The NAME string gadget defines the button name.
  
  The COMMAND string gadget defines the command path and command name.

  The ADD Gadget adds one button.

  The INSERT gadget inserts one button.

  The SWITCH gadget switches positions of two buttons.

  The COPY gadget copies a button to another position.

  The REMOVE gadget removes (deletes) a selected button.

  The SET WIDTH text string gadget defines the width of the button.

  The ABOUT gadget gives program information.

  The PALETTE strips define foreground (text) and background (back)
  colors.

  The SAVE gadget saves the configuration.

  The USE gadget uses but does not save the configuration.

  The CANCEL gadget cancels everything.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  The Configuration window must be open. Click an "active" button
  with the RMB to open the Configuration window.

@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    16                      - BEGIN NODE TYPES -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE TYPES
@TITLE "16 The Button Types"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN} @{" The Master Button " LINK MASTER}

                         @{B}The Button Types@{UB}

  TheBoss allows three selectable button types: Drawer, Executable and
  Script. There is a gadget for each type. Only one type can be used
  for a button.

  1. The DRAWER is a drawer or directory button. It is used to open
     another button panel (or bank) containing other buttons. The
     opened button panel can have just one button or many and have
     a mixture of button types. The Drawer button requires a name only.
     Arguments are not required.

  2. The EXECUTABLE runs programs. The Executable button is an "action"
     button. Clicking an Executable button with the LMB runs the
     selected program. The Executable button requires a name and a
     full path to the program. The Executable button is the default
     button type.

  3. The SCRIPT executes a script file. The required "execute" command
     is built-in. The script can be any script. There is no special
     script requirements. Scripts with the "s" protection bit set are
     treated as executables. If scripts are run as executables, it is
     prudent to still set the Script type. The purpose is to distinquish
     between an executable program and an executable script. The Script
     button requires a name and full path to the script.

  Experimentation is the best way to learn how to use these button types
  in conjunction with each other. Do not be afraid to experiment. It
  is the best way to learn TheBoss.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  When TheBoss is first run, a button labeled "New" appears at the upper
  left of the screen. This is the "master" button. The button label can
  be changed to any label (or name) desired. This button must be a Drawer
  button. If the type is not changed to Drawer, then TheBoss configuration 
  file will consist of only one button. It is very important to fully
  understand this important fact. The initial "master" button must be a
  Drawer button because it is the gateway to all TheBoss is and can be.

@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    17                      - BEGIN NODE NAME -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE NAME
@TITLE "17 Name & Command"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                           @{B}Name & Command@{UB}

  The NAME text string gadget is for the button name. It can be any
  name desired.

  The COMMAND text string gadget is for the full path to and name of
  the executable program or script. Full path and name follow the
  usual convention. Be very sure path and name are correct.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Button names can be any name. Buttons don't care what their name is.
  However, descriptive button names are best suited. Descriptive names
  describe what the button is or does.

  The full command path and name is an absolute requirement for all
  Executable and Script buttons. There are no exceptions.

@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    18                      - BEGIN NODE ADD -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE ADD
@TITLE "18 The Add Gadget"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}
   
                          @{B}The Add Gadget@{UB}

  The ADD gadget adds one button directly beneath the last button or,
  in the case of a button panel, beneath the last bottom button.
 
  The Add gadget strictly adds only one button. It does not add multiple
  buttons. The default Add button is an Executable button.

  Click the Add gadget with either LMB or RMB. The Configuration window
  will close/reopen. Click either Use or Save and the button is added.
  The Configuration window always closes with Use and Save. Use RMB to
  reopen window. Repeat to add more buttons.

                             @{B}A Hint@{UB}

  Before clicking Use or Save select a button type other than the default
  Executable type. Now click Use or Save. Repeat the Add process. The
  button type is the same. TheBoss remembers the previous button type.

  If a button is added after a button at the very bottom of the screen,
  the added button will not be seen. To see the added button, the button
  panel must be dragged up from the bottom of the screen. It is always
  better to drag the button panel up before adding buttons. The button
  panel is not pushed up automatically by the added button.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  There is no provision for multiple button adds. This feature may be
  implimented in a future version.

  There is no provision for cross panel adds. This feature will never
  be implimented. There is absolutely no need.

@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    19                      - BEGIN NODE INSERT -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE INSERT
@TITLE "19 The Insert Gadget"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                         @{B}The Insert Gadget@{UB}

  The INSERT gadget inserts a button directly above a selected button.
  Insert always inserts above and never below a selected button.

  Using Insert is easy. Select an active button and click with RMB.
  The Configuration will open. Click Insert. The Configuration window
  quickly closes/reopens. Click either Use or Save and the inserted
  button magically appears.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Insert is a powerful tool for correcting configuration errors or,
  if used in conjunction with other gadgets, a still more powerful
  tool for reordering an entire panel structure or configuration.


@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    20                      - BEGIN NODE SWITCH -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE SWITCH
@TITLE "20 The Switch Gadget"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                         @{B}The Switch Gadget@{UB}

  The SWITCH gadget switches the positions of two selected buttons.
  Switch on switches positions. It does nothing more.

  Switch behaves differently than Insert. Select an active and click
  with RMB. The Configuration window opens. Click Switch. The window
  closes and does not reopen. Use LMB/RMB and select a button. Now
  select another button. The two buttons switch places. Go on to
  other operations. The next time the configuration is saved, Save
  will save the new button positions.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Switch is another powerful editing tool in TheBoss arsenal of gadgets.
  Unlike Add and Insert, Switch will switch buttons across button panels.
  It is very useful in reorganizing entire panel structures.

@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    21                      - BEGIN NODE COPY -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE COPY
@TITLE "21 The Copy Gadget"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN} @{" Switch " LINK SWITCH}

                          @{B}The Copy Gadget@{UB}

  The COPY gadget copies a button. Copy equally copies a selected button
  to another position within a button panel or to another another button
  panel. Copy creates exact duplicates of a selected button. The copied
  button will overwrite a previously configured button.

  Copy behaves exactly like Switch. If Switch is understood, then Copy
  follows suit. The same procedure applies. Review Switch for details.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Unlike any other function, Copy will overwrite a previously configured
  button. Use caution to prevent overwrites. Copy does not have a
  confirmatory requestor. One may be added with the next TheBoss version
  as an overwrite cautionary.

  If used with care, Copy really speeds up button panel revisions or
  aids in creating new button and/or button panel configurations. Copy
  is of immense value if used properly.

@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    22                      - BEGIN NODE REMOVE -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE REMOVE
@TITLE "22 The Remove Gadget"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                         @{B}The Remove Gadget@{UB}

  The REMOVE gadget removes a selected button. Just as Add adds, Remove
  removes. Remove has a confirmatory requestor. The Remove action must be
  confirmed before executed. The requestor requires a Yes/No click to
  remove the selected button.

  Remove works the same as the other gadgets. Select an active button
  with the RMB. The Configuration window opens. Click remove. The Remove
  requestor appears asking for confirmation. Click either Yes or No. If
  Yes is clicked, the button is removed. If No is clicked, the removal
  is aborted.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Of all TheBoss functions, Remove is the most serious. Remove seems
  simple. Remove removes a button. Simple. Nothing more to be said.

  Remove is more complex than simple button removal. Remove can remove
  entire button panels if button panels are associated to the removed
  button. Remove removes everything associated with a button. Removing
  Executable or Script buttons is not dangerous because they are easily
  replaced. A Drawer button is another matter. If a Drawer button is
  removed, everything that button may open is lost as well. The is no
  recourse. TheBoss configuration file has been rewritten eliminating
  all traces of the removed button and anything attached to it.

  Best advice is to know what is being removed when Remove is selected.
  Be sure before the Yes gadget is clicked that the selected button
  does require removal. Only remove when certain what is being removed
  should be removed. There is no recourse and no mercy.

@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    23                      - BEGIN NODE ABOUT -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE ABOUT
@TITLE "23 The About Gadget"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                          @{B}The About Gadget@{UB}

  The ABOUT gadget displays information about TheBoss and registrant.
  The About also appears as the first window an unregistered user
  sees when starting TheBoss. Registered users do not see this window
  on startup.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  All programs have an "About" giving program information. TheBoss
  is no different.

@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    24                      - BEGIN NODE WIDTH -

  ********************************************************************

@NODE WIDTH
@TITLE "The Set Width Field"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                         @{B}The Set Width Field@{UB}

  The SET WIDTH function allows setting button width. The default width
  is 65 pixels. This value (in pixels) can be changed to any value
  approaching screen resolution width. It can not exceed the screen
  mode horizontal resolution. Any Set Width value between the default and
  the maximum is fine. The value can approach but not be the maximum
  value.

  All single button panels or larger multiple button panels can have
  different widths. Narrow and wide panels co-exist well within the same
  configuration. However, all buttons of the same panel will be the
  same width. Buttons can not be of differing sizes within a panel. If
  the panel size is changed, all the buttons also change to the new
  width size.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  The most powerful feature of Set Width is allowing many interesting
  configuration possibilities. Various width button panels integrated
  properly can be attractive and appealing. Experiment with Set Width.
  It is a solid TheBoss feature.

@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    25                      - BEGIN NODE COLORS -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE COLORS
@TITLE "25 The Palette Colors"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                         @{B}The Palette Colors@{UB}

  PALETTE is divided into two color strips: Foreground (text) and
  Background (back) colors. The default colors are pen 0 and pen 1.
  Pen 0 can vary from system to system. Pen 1 is usually black.

  The palette is first 16 colors of the Workbench palette. If the  
  Workbench colors are changed, TheBoss palette will change likewise.
  Whatever colors are available in the Workbench palette are available
  in TheBoss palette.

  Any combination of color can be used for button colors. Only one each
  of the foreground and background colors may be used.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  TheBoss remembers selected colors. If colors are selected and additional
  buttons are added to a panel, TheBoss will remember the colors and all
  added buttons will use the same colors. This will continue until the colors
  are changed to new colors.

  Future version of TheBoss will include expanded palette options. Until
  that time, the 16 color Workbench palette will have to serve. Depending
  what the Workbench color are, many interesting color combinations are
  possible.

@ENDNODE

