    26                     - BEGIN NODE START -  

   ********************************************************************

@NODE START
@TITLE "26 Starting TheBoss"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN} @{" The Master Button " LINK MASTER}

                          @{B}Starting TheBoss@{UB}

  Before starting TheBoss for the first time, please setup the initial
  configuration in Preferences. This is very important and should not
  be skipped. Initial configuration may save disappointment on how
  TheBoss first appears.

  The first thing seen when TheBoss is first started is a small button
  labeled "New" upper left on the screen. This is the "Master" button.
  The Master button is so important that it will be treated separately
  in this guide.

  The appearance of this button is determined by what options were
  selected in Preferences/options.

  If the button has a title bar, it is the default Title Bar option. If
  it does not have a title bar, then it is the Borderless option.

  Both these option button types have a drag bar. For the Title Bar
  button, the title bar is the drag bar. For the Borderless, there
  is a small drag gadget to the right. Drag the button to any desired
  location.

  Click the button with the RMB to open the Configuration window. The
  button label "New" is within NAME text string gadget. "New" may be
  erased and replaced by a more appropriate name. The button label
  "New" only appears on a newly generated button from a LMB click on
  a Drawer button. No other time. Only Drawer button can create other
  buttons that can become button panels. Executable and Script buttons
  can not generate new buttons.

  All new buttons are Executable buttons. If left as an Executable
  button, that's where TheBoss ends. This is the whole configuration.
  So, change the Executable button to a Drawer button and click Use.

  Click the button with the LMB and another button appears upper left
  labeled "New". This new button is the start of a button panel. The 
  very first button can be the first button of a button panel, too.
  But it best left as a single button panel. Refer to The Master Button
  for the reasons why.

  If familiar with the gadgets from reading the Configuration Window
  section, now is the time to start playing with TheBoss. Begin to
  feel the power in action.

                              @{B}Comment@{UB}

  All the Configuration Window gadgets are intuitive enough to figure
  out without reading documents. Just a matter of seeing what works
  and what doesn't. TheBoss was designed with this intuitive concept
  in mind. Absolutely no harm can be done to any system from playing
  with TheBoss to see how it works. A system might crash. But even
  that is not likely. Best advice is play and learn. This is practice.
  Just have fun. Get serious later.

@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    27                      - BEGIN NODE QUIT -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE QUIT
@TITLE " 27 Quitting TheBoss" @{" The Master Button " LINK MASTER}
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                          @{B}Quitting TheBoss@{UB}

  How to quit/exit a program is as important as how to start a program.
  TheBoss makes it easy. There are completely different ways to quit/
  exit TheBoss.

  1. Just press the <ESC> key. TheBoss quits/exits immediately. This
     key press is the "Quick/Express" quit/exit. A good way to quit/
     exit if no changes have been made. If changes have been made,
     click any active button with the RMB and save. Then use <ESC>.

  2. Remember the mention of the Master button? The Master button is
     the only other way to quit/exit TheBoss.

     Every first button (or header button) of every button panel
     has a "Close" gadget. All except the Master button close
     their pane. The Master button "Close" gadget quits/exits
     TheBoss.

     This "Close" gadget is dependent on whether Exit Remember is
     enabled or not. If Exit Remember is not enabled, clicking the
     "Close" gadget opens a quit requestor with Yes/No options.

     If Exit Remember is enable an additional "Save Changes" requestor
     follows with Yes/No options.

   The only other way to quit/exit TheBoss is to reboot the system.
   But that way quits/exits everything, doesn't it?

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

   How to quit/exit TheBoss? Depends on the circumstances and whether
   the Exit Remember option is enabled or not.


@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    28                     - BEGIN NODE MASTER -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE MASTER
@TITLE "28 The Master Button"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                        @{B}The Master Button@{UB}

  The Master button is called the Master button for lack of a better
  name. It is the first button TheBoss generates on initial startup.
  It is the only button whose "Close" gadget can quit/exit TheBoss.
  The entire configuration depends on how the Master button is used.

  There are some "loose" guidelines for the Master button that ought
  to be followed. They are breakable guidelines. There is no required
  need to follow them.

  1. Never hide the Master button. Never conceal it behind a panel.
     If it must be hidden, hide in plain sight. The Workbench title
     bar right is a good place. Adjust Set Width to a comfortable
     width. Change background color to the title bar color. Add text.
     Not recomended. Makes the button conspicuous. This is just one
     way. But there others to make TheMaster part of the landscape.
     Hiding in plain sight allows access to the Master button "kill"
     switch, the "Close" gadget.
     
  2. Never use the Master button as an Executable button. Do it and
     find out why. Always configure as a Drawer button.

  3. Never add buttons to the Master button. The reasons. Absolutely
     no need to do so. Just makes the Master button conspicuous.
     Let the other buttons do the work.

  4. Never use the first button generated by the Master as Drawer
     button. Leave it as an Executable button. Add Drawer buttons.
     Keep the number of added buttons minmum. Use this button as
     the Control button. The Master button without being the Master
     button.

  5. Never even think (or consider) removing the Master button. Removal
     will destory the entire configuration.

  Other guideslines could be added. But for all practical purposes,
  these five guidelines are all that's necessary.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Always remember to protect the Master button. It is vital to TheBoss.



@ENDNODE
 
   ********************************************************************

    29                     - BEGIN NODE STARTUP -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE STARTUP
@TITLE "29 The Startup Options
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}

                           @{B}The Startup Options@{UB}

  There are three ways to run TheBoss: The Program Icon, The WBStartup
  Drawer and The User-Startup.

  The Program icon is the easiest way to start TheBoss. No point further
  explaining this method.

                            @{B}The WBStartup Drawer@{UB}

  The WBStartup drawers offer a couple different options. The first is
  to use TheBoss and its icon. The second to use a "project" icon.
  Either method requires the "TheBoss.pref" file in the WBStartup drawer.
  This file is absolutely necessary. TheBoss will start without it but
  won't be useful. TheBoss needs "TheBoss.pref" file to be present in
  the same directory. It is TheBoss configuration file.

  To use TheBoss and its icon is not a good way. The main reason is that
  it separates TheBoss from its preferences utility. Copy the Preferences
  solves nothing. Merely adds to the problem. Don't use this method. Not 
  recommended. Moreover, this method requires two distinct directories
  with TheBoss in each, the Programdir and the WBstartup drawer.

  The best way is to use a project icon. Name the project icon the same 
  as the TheBoss configuration file, TheBoss.pref. Set the default tool
  as TheBoss with full path to the programdir. Set the icon tooltype
  "DoNotwait". That's it. TheBoss will run from the WBStartup drawer.

                             @{B}The User-Startup@{UB}

  The user-startup option is the best way to run TheBoss. Add the
  following lines to the very end of the user-startup:

      CD XXX:TheBoss             Example: CD DH0:Utilities/TheBoss
      Run >NIL: TheBoss                   Run >NIL: TheBoss

  The reason to add these lines to the very end of the user-startup
  is to insure the Workbench and TheBoss interface appear virtually
  simultaneously. If scripted earlier in the user-startup, TheBoss
  will run before the Workbench loads.

  The Run >NIL: redirection allows closing the shell window. TheBoss
  will run with the redirection. But the results are not pretty. The
  "Runback" command may also be used.

  Another hybrid method is to write script with and protect with the
  S bit set. Copy the script to the S directory and add the following
  line (again at the end) of the user-startup:

      S:<script name>            Example: S:Boss.Startup

  Since the S protection bit is set, the script is treated as an
  executable file, and TheBoss runs.

  This method keeps all TheBoss resources in the programdir. Allows 
  easy access to TheBoss preferences. Doesn't require a completely
  isolated TheBoss copy in the WBStartup drawer.

  Note: There are other ways to run TheBoss using utilities available
        on the Aminet. Both Toolmanager and ToolsDaemon run TheBoss
        without any problem.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Curious to note that this guide should mention programs TheBoss
  hopes to replace. Both Toolmanager and ToolsDaemon are good programs,
  but TheBoss is a better system manager.

@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    30                    - BEGIN NODE SCRIPTS -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE SCRIPTS
@TITLE "30 Why Use Scripts?"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN}
   
                          @{B}Why Use Scripts?@[UB}

  The simple answer is "Why not?". Scripts can do some very good things.
  It all depends on how scripts are used and why.

  TheBoss uses scripts as a button type. Actually, the script button
  type is the usual AmigaDOS scripts that require execution with the
  AmigaDOS execute command. Scripts with the "s" protection bit set
  run as executables; therefore, can be treated as executables. However,
  it is a good practice to indicate the type as script just for reference
  purposes.

  It is a good idea to keep all TheBoss related scripts in TheBoss
  programdir in a subdirectory "Scripts". Further subdirectories may
  be created for general categories such as Applications, Graphics,
  Music, etc. Keeping all TheBoss scripts in the programdir is better
  than further cluttering up the S directory with more scripts.

  TheBoss has a problem with executables with arguments. There is no
  point in concealing this shortcoming. It is readily apparent if anyone
  uses TheBoss for any length of time. Here is where scripting steps
  in as a remedy. Scripts allow TheBoss to do pretty much anything one
  can imagine. So do include scripts as part of what TheBoss can do for
  you.

  Project icons are another problem for TheBoss. A solution to this
  problem is inevitable. However, in the meantime, use scripts to run
  a program's projects, or simply load them into the program itself.

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  The use of scripts only augments TheBoss' capabilities. Use them well.
  And use them often. They will support the simple answer "Why not?".  

@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    31                      - BEGIN NODE TIPS -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE TIPS 
@TITLE "31 Tips & Tricks"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN} @{" Author " LINK AUTHOR}

                           @{B}Tips & Tricks@{UB}

  It's difficult to reduce experience with TheBoss to a few tips and
  tricks. No doubt, as the knowledge of a program increases, little
  shortcuts emerge to speed things along. It's natural for that to
  happen. Please do pass those little "gems" of information on to 
  the Author. He prefers that kind of information to "bug" reports.

  Because TheBoss is so new, there are few hard, fast rules. But are 
  a few things to be aware of and keep in mind. Consider these "tips"
  not so much as "tips" but as a sensible approach toward configuring
  TheBoss.

   1. Remember TheBoss configuration is unlimited. The number of buttons
      is infinite. Impose finite limits. Do not configure just to
      configure more buttons. That will lead to a labyrinth.

   2. Keep the configuration simple. Devise a plan. Know what the goal
      is. Don't treat TheBoss as a toy. It is a very serious program
      that can do much to make system management easy.

   3. Keep directory panels separate from program panels. Think of them
      as "apples" and "oranges". Try not to intermix directories and
      programs together on the same panel. If unavoidable, use color
      codes to assure separation.

   4. Use device button panels. This is a good way to handle ZIP drives
      or other occasional use devices. If a system has multiple partitions,
      a device button panel may be the best approach.

   5. Try to avoid directory layers. Layers means directory buttons
      accessing more directory button panels which in turn access more
      directory button panels. The result is a pyramid of directory panels
      without purpose or function. Pretty soon, a "travel" guide is needed
      to know what's what.

   6. Group programs by type. Keep graphics with graphics. Keep utilities
      with utilities. Don't mix and try to match. Doesn't work well.
      Only leads to confusion. Keep like things together even if there
      are only a couple on a panel.

   7. Never discard an old configuration until it's totally useless.
      Create a directory for it in the programdir. Copy it and TheBoss
      into that directory. Run TheBoss using the old configuration file 
      from a script button in the current configuration file. Acts as
      a good reference. Delete configuration only when drained of all
      useful information. Copy TheBoss Preferences into that directory.
      Use Preferences to start a new configuration for development or
      experimental reasons. TheBoss Preferences runs directly from an
      executable button. No script is required. Good way to test ideas.

   8. Never worry about configuration errors. Consider the errors as
      gaining experience and move on. If it takes twenty configurations
      to get it right, that's twenty configurations worth of experience.
      Just imagine how many configurations have passed through TheBoss
      during development and beta testing.

   9. Always keep a backup copy of the configuration file. Keep it
      somewhere safe. Use a script to copy the current configuration
      to the backup location.

  10. If a registered user, the same goes for your keyfile. All keyfiles
      are unique. There is no general keyfile. If yours is lost for any
      reason, you must get a new keyfile from Fantaisie Software.

  None of the above are written in stone. They are just general points
  to be aware of. Keep the configuration as simple as possible, but
  not simpler. Simple enough to do the job but no simpler. 

                              @{B}Comments@{UB}

  Do write the Author about little "things" you discover. He would be
  delighted to hear from you. An e-mail doesn't take very long to do.

@ENDNODE

   ********************************************************************

    32                     - BEGIN NODE COMMENTS -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE COMMENTS
@TITLE "32 General Comments"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN} @{" Author  " LINK AUTHOR}

                       @{B}General Comments@{UB}

  TheBoss is a good system management program. It is small, fast and
  flexible to meet changing system requirement. Configuration is fast
  and easy free of cumbersome requirements. Make the configuration
  as simple or complex as wanted. TheBoss will meet legitimate needs
  without any hassle or problems.

  But TheBoss does have limitations. All software products do. The
  job of a programmer is to push back the limitations and find new
  ways to do things previously not done. TheBoss is programmed to
  meet this standard. There is no current program like TheBoss
  currently available now. There are available software products
  that attempt to do what TheBoss does so well. These products have
  all sorts of special requirements. Or take an enormous of time
  and effort to configure. Most are much larger than TheBoss. Some
  3-5 times larger in size. Many are memory hungry draining available
  memory quickly. Some don't release the memory back to the memory
  pool effectively on exit. Many use external interfaces (MUI and
  Classact). TheBoss does not. TheBoss draws only on its internal
  resources letting other programs use external resources.

  Another plus is that TheBoss does not spread itself out to other
  directories. There are no TheBoss preferences in Prefs/Env-Archive.
  There is no TheBoss Preferences in the Prefs drawer. Everything
  exists solely in the programdir and no place else. No need to
  search for other associated files. Just delete TheBoss directory
  and TheBoss is gone.

  There are other files. If TheBoss is run from the WBStartup drawer,
  there are two files there. If TheBoss is run from the user-startup,
  there are some lines to delete. The difference is that these additions
  are user choices. They are not required by TheBoss. The user chooses
  to run TheBoss from the WBStartup drawer or the user-startup. TheBoss
  had no part in selecting those options. Moreover, there are no
  assignments in the user-startup to remove if TheBoss is deleted from
  the system.

  All these things make TheBoss a good program to have and use. Future
  TheBoss versions will never compromise the basic concept fundamental
  to TheBoss: the user must control his system. Software only helps.

  TheBoss only helps manage a system because the system user is TheBoss.

@ENDNODE

   ******************************************************************** 

    33                     - BEGIN NODE FUTURE -

   ********************************************************************

@NODE FUTURE
@TITLE "33 Future Features?"
@{"  Main   " LINK MAIN} @{" Registration " LINK REGISTER}
   
                          @{B}TheBoss Future@{UB}

  Not everything that was to be included is included in this TheBoss
  release. Additional features were intentially held for future versions
  for developmental reasons and a personal reason. The personal reason
  being to measure response to the first TheBoss release. If the response
  is poor, why spend time, money and energy on a "dead" project. If the
  response is favorable, then TheBoss will be continued and further
  developed. The future of TheBoss is really in the hands of the Amiga
  community. This is good software. Hope the Amiga community agrees and
  registers TheBoss.

               @{B}New Features for TheBoss And Preferences@{UB}

   * Column support. Button panels with multiple columns of buttons.
     Includes all configuration operations similar to buttons.
   * Panel specific option selections. Different look for individual
     panels.
   * Increase global options. Adding top and left drag bar options.
   * Increased font selection. Different panels using different fonts.
   * Better icon tooltype and argument support.
   * Increase palette color to 32 colors (maybe 256 colors).
   * Allow slectable color palettes: Workbench, user custom and original
     (TheBoss default colors).
   * Entirely new Preferences with different windows and look. Maybe
     just one window for all parts.
   * Special application shape buttons: square, circle, etc.
   * New configuration window incorporating new added features.
   * Possible pattern support for buttons. Nice little pattern on
     button background.
   * Button or panel lockout feature. Protects sensitive buttons or
     panels. Password requestor unlock.
   * Multiple configuration support. Ability to select desired
     configuration.
   * Hotkey iconify to screen title bar.
   * Further optimize memory utilitization. Further reduce memory
     consumption.
   * Possible no removal option.
   * Possible Arexx script support.
   * Further optimize all code for speed and size. TheBoss is small
     and fast. Make still smaller and faster.
   * Plus any practical user suggestions...

   TheBoss will never use MUI, Classact or the like. TheBoss will
   never use menus.

   Not all of the features listed above are realistic and doable
   without a dramatic increase in program size and speed. But most
   are.

   Would truly appreciate honest comment about TheBoss any features that
   should be added. Such comments will be considered very carefully. No
   suggestion is to trival. A small sugestion might turn into a very
   good feature.

                              Comments

   The ultimate goal for TheBoss is to be the best system manager
   available. Do support the process and register TheBoss.

@ENDNODE

